b'' b'the *security* of the system does depend only on the secrecy of the keys.' b'' b'the ability to tap is an inherent *insecurity* which depends fundamentally on' b'the secrecy of the algorithm. to spell it out, because so many people seem to' b'miss the point, if the algorithm were published, anyone could create a chip' b'which would work correctly with the skipjack chips but which would not have' b'its key registered.' b'' b'i believe there is no technical means of ensuring key escrow without the' b'government maintaining a secret of some kind. for example, the secret could be' b'the private keys of the escrow agencies; their digital signatures would be' b'required before a key could be used. in this case, the nsa/nist/whoever has' b'decided that protecting the entire algorithm is easier/cheaper/more secure than' b'other possible protocols.' b'' b'--' b'materials molecular simulation center, caltech' b'henry spencer left-of-|, margaret puckette signature fan' 